      <hedline>
        <hl1>Nursing Home Reports</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jeff Seagall letter comments on July 23 article on US recommendations for strict new rules governing operation of nursing homes</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U.S. Recommending Strict New Rules at Nursing Homes'' (front page, July 23): The eight-year delay in the delivery of this report is explained by the need to analyze huge amounts of data from nursing homes around the country.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U.S. Recommending Strict New Rules at Nursing Homes'' (front page, July 23): The eight-year delay in the delivery of this report is explained by the need to analyze huge amounts of data from nursing homes around the country.</p>
        <p>Shouldn't the results be published and made available to consumers on a state-by-state basis, a national nursing home report card, if you will, so that families can make informed decisions about the best nursing homes to care for their loved ones?</p>
        <p>Furthermore, shouldn't it be mandated that all coroners' offices send detailed reports of cause of death to a national clearinghouse that will be the source of annually issued nursing home ''report card'' updates?</p>
        <p>JEFF SEAGALL  New York, July 23, 2000</p>
        <p>Correction:  July 27, 2000, Thursday  Because of a typographical error, a letter yesterday about nursing homes misspelled the writer's surname. He is Jeff Segall, not Seagall.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="correction_text">
        <p>Correction: July 27, 2000, Thursday</p>
        <p>Because of a typographical error, a letter yesterday about nursing homes misspelled the writer's surname. He is Jeff Segall, not Seagall.</p>
        <p>&lt;br&gt;</p>
      </block>
